# Vagrantfile Best Practices

## Configuration Standards
- Always use Vagrant.configure("2") for version compatibility
- Include proper Ruby mode and encoding comments at the top
- Use descriptive comments for each configuration section

## Network Configuration
- Use private networks with specific IP ranges (192.168.56.x)
- Configure public networks with bridge adapter for external access
- Avoid port forwarding unless specifically required
- Use consistent network adapter naming

## Box Selection
- Ubuntu: Use `ubuntu/focal64` (20.04) or `ubuntu/jammy64` (22.04)
- CentOS: Use `eurolinux-vagrant/centos-stream-9`
- Always specify exact box versions for reproducibility

## Resource Allocation
- Memory: 1024MB default, 1600MB for application servers
- CPU: Use default unless specific requirements
- Storage: Use default unless large storage needed

## Provisioning
- Use shell provisioning for simple setups
- Include package installation and service configuration
- Clean up temporary files after provisioning
- Use inline scripts for small configurations

## Provider Configuration
- VirtualBox is the primary provider
- Configure memory allocation in provider block
- Disable GUI unless debugging required

## File Structure
- Each VM should have its own directory
- Use descriptive directory names (e.g., wordpressIAC, finance)
- Keep Vagrantfile in the root of each VM directory
